182
00:15:48,960 --> 00:15:56,760
were just sort of quivering, waiting for the shoe 
to drop. And the product's launched, but you would  

183
00:15:56,760 --> 00:16:02,160
never be able to look at our numbers and see when 
that happened. And the press often writes about  

184
00:16:02,160 --> 00:16:08,160
competition like, "Oh, it's a shotgun blast."
When, later, I would learn it's more of a boa  

185
00:16:08,160 --> 00:16:17,120
constrictor. But the end of that first chapter 
really culminated in us recognizing that we  

186
00:16:17,120 --> 00:16:20,720
experienced a lot of benefits of being this 
kind of product for everyone. And in fact,  

187
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:25,480
it would be kind of hard for me to describe in the 
early days who Dropbox is for, or what it does. It  

188
00:16:25,480 --> 00:16:32,280
was similar to what's a phone for, or what's a 
computer for? And in the beginning, that was a  

189
00:16:32,280 --> 00:16:36,480
blessing. It meant that those viral loops would 
really work. Pretty much everybody you would  

190
00:16:36,480 --> 00:16:42,040
hit would have a need for something like Dropbox. 
Either a personal need, or a work need, or both. 

191
00:16:42,920 --> 00:16:48,880
But we recognized even back then before 
competition that, "Hey, people are using us  

192
00:16:48,880 --> 00:16:54,440
primarily for things like backup, backing up their 
devices, or storage. People are using us for photo  

193
00:16:54,440 --> 00:17:02,560
sharing. People are using us as a collaborative 
space at work, and often, in huge companies."  

194
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:10,000
And then, we felt that there was a lot of tension 
between these use cases. So for example, the ideal  

195
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:14,320
file server replacement for an IT admin is going 
to look quite different from the ideal consumer  

196
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:19,360
photo sharing app. And we also recognize things 
like, "Well, we're going to be competing in many  

197
00:17:19,360 --> 00:17:24,120
cases with the device, or the operating system."
When you look at something like iCloud, it's like,  

198
00:17:24,120 --> 00:17:28,080
"Yeah. When you turn on your iPhone for the first 
time, it's probably not going to give you an ad  

199
00:17:28,080 --> 00:17:34,320
for Dropbox." So we're like, "Hey, we need to 
address some of these issues," and expanded to  

200
00:17:34,320 --> 00:17:42,240
some new areas to diversify. The first two 
things we did were, after getting enough  

201
00:17:42,240 --> 00:17:46,840
complaints from IT administrators asking us what 
the hell these photo sharing features were for,  

202
00:17:46,840 --> 00:17:52,480
we pulled all the photo sharing functionality out 
into a separate and new app we called Carousel.  

203
00:17:53,040 --> 00:17:59,040
Where the basic value prop was phones, to that 
point, were limited in their storage by the  

204
00:17:59,040 --> 00:18:01,840
amount of physical storage on the device.
We're like, "This is silly. You should be  

205
00:18:01,840 --> 00:18:06,320
able to have your whole life in your pocket." 
So be able to store everything in the cloud,  

206
00:18:06,320 --> 00:18:10,920
but have the experience be as if everything 
were locally there through a lot of caching,  

207
00:18:10,920 --> 00:18:15,040
and sleight of hand, and thumbnails, and things 
like that. So there's much engineering there.  

208
00:18:15,040 --> 00:18:17,680
And then, secondly, we saw people were 
using us at work, and we're like, "Well,  

209
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:22,200
there's a lot of different adjacent workflows." 
And there was a startup called Mailbox that built  

210
00:18:22,200 --> 00:18:26,280
the first great mobile email client. Had a lot of 
funny parallels. They had a [inaudible 00:18:26]-

211
00:18:26,280 --> 00:18:28,120
Oh, that's right. They're 
famous for that waitlist.

212
00:18:28,120 --> 00:18:28,440
Yeah.

213
00:18:28,440 --> 00:18:29,200
That's a really good point.

214
00:18:29,200 --> 00:18:29,780
Which was crazy.

215
00:18:29,780 --> 00:18:30,080
Yeah.

216
00:18:30,080 --> 00:18:34,240
And so we're like, "I don't know. Maybe this is 
going to be our Instagram," and so we bought those  

217
00:18:34,240 --> 00:18:40,640
guys. And then 2014, I'm on stage painting 
this picture of Dropbox's future. I'm like,  

218
00:18:40,640 --> 00:18:47,120
"We're going to help be the way that you remember 
your life. We're going to be your productivity.  

219
00:18:47,120 --> 00:18:54,800
The new productivity suite on your phone," and 
all these things. But then it was this dissonance  

220
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:59,360
where there were so many things that were going 
right, and certainly the numbers, user numbers,  

221
00:18:59,360 --> 00:19:05,160
revenue numbers. We were sort of accidentally 
cash flow positive maybe a year after launching. 

222
00:19:05,880 --> 00:19:15,360
It was also clear that winter was coming, or 
that things weren't exactly as they seemed.  

223
00:19:17,400 --> 00:19:25,760
Then the start of the second chapter, 2015, I'd 
start to hear a louder set of critics inside,  

224
00:19:25,760 --> 00:19:31,000
and outside the company. And I'd been 
thinking for a long time like, "All right,  

225
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:37,080
man, we're really fighting wars on all these 
very disparate fronts." We're with storage.  

226
00:19:37,080 --> 00:19:41,440
We're competing with the device to back up 
the device with photo sharing, or competing  

227
00:19:41,440 --> 00:19:50,720
with Facebook, Snap, Instagram, Google, Apple.
On productivity, we're competing with Microsoft,  

228
00:19:50,720 --> 00:19:56,520
and Google. And then, there's a whole new 
cohort of companies like Slack. And then,  

229
00:19:57,040 --> 00:20:01,520
there's this experience of one day I am standing 
on stage talking about how Carousel, and Mailbox,  

230
00:20:01,520 --> 00:20:06,600
and everything are the future of the company. 
Less than a year later, Google Photos launches.  

231
00:20:07,320 --> 00:20:16,080
And not only does it provide a lot of the same 
value, and in many ways very inspired by what we  

232
00:20:16,080 --> 00:20:23,920
had done, but they also gave you free unlimited 
storage for life. Not just photos, but video. 

233
00:20:23,920 --> 00:20:31,160
And so they just totally nuked our business 
model in ways that were bad enough in terms  

234
00:20:31,160 --> 00:20:38,640
of just their obvious impact, but even worse 
because it was so easily anticipated. So this  

235
00:20:38,640 --> 00:20:48,280
became a very public, and personal embarrassment 
for me. How could we not have predicted that,  

236
00:20:48,280 --> 00:20:53,080
or been out in front of that? And then, 
that started this period. I'd say that was  

237
00:20:53,080 --> 00:20:59,560
the beginning of chapter two where it was we 
went from the company that could do no wrong  

238
00:20:59,560 --> 00:21:07,240
to the company that could do no right, which 
was a big flip. It was probably early summer,  

239
00:21:07,240 --> 00:21:11,320
maybe late spring, when Google Photos launched.
At first, I'm just thinking like, "Okay. This  

240
00:21:11,320 --> 00:21:19,720
was a big miss on my part. How do we get out of 
this? We need to tackle some of these competitive  

241
00:21:19,720 --> 00:21:28,640
issues much more ahead on." And then, what's the 
problem? Well, the problem is that every incumbent  

242
00:21:28,640 --> 00:21:34,560
is going to copy your product. They're 
going to bundle it with our platforms,  

243
00:21:34,560 --> 00:21:39,000
and then they're going to kill the economics. 
And that was clear what was going to happen  

244
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:45,080
with Google Photos. It was very similar product 
experience bundled with Android, bundled with all  

245
00:21:46,440 --> 00:21:55,200
of Google's different touch points, and then free.
So that was problematic enough for Carousel,  

246
00:21:55,200 --> 00:21:58,640
but I'm like, "Wait, this is going to happen 
with everything that we're doing. Same thing  

247
00:21:58,640 --> 00:22:03,480
with Mailbox." I had even pitch the founders to 
join Dropbox by saying, "Look, you're going to  

248
00:22:03,480 --> 00:22:08,800
wake up tomorrow, and Gmail, and Apple Mail, and 
everything is just going to have these swipes and  

249
00:22:08,800 --> 00:22:19,160
snoozes. The UI, it's not a durable source of 
advantage. We'll buy that problem from you." 

250
00:22:19,160 --> 00:22:25,160
And that's exactly what happened. So I'm 
like, "All right. Even in theory, how do we  

251
00:22:25,160 --> 00:22:31,000
deal with this?" And I'd gotten the criticism 
over the years that Dropbox is a commodity,  

252
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:34,080
and investors in the early days would be like, 
"Hey, this is kind a graveyard of a space,  

253
00:22:34,080 --> 00:22:44,800
and DOA." And I thought, "Well, how do other 
companies deal with this kind of competition,  

254
00:22:44,800 --> 00:22:53,240
and commodities?" So there's a great book by AG 
Lafley and Roger Martin called Playing to Win.

255
00:22:53,240 --> 00:22:54,760
Roger's been on the podcast.

256
00:22:54,760 --> 00:23:00,880
Yeah. I'm a huge fan of Roger's. And I was 
like, "All right. Well, if we think we're  

257
00:23:00,880 --> 00:23:07,640
selling a commodity, try literally selling paper 
towels." Which is what AG, and Procter & Gamble,  

258
00:23:07,640 --> 00:23:13,880
and a lot of CPG companies do. And AG was the CEO 
of Procter & Gamble at the time. And basically,  

259
00:23:13,880 --> 00:23:22,040
he and Roger did this download of how they think 
about competition, and markets, and advantage.  

260
00:23:24,120 --> 00:23:28,520
And a lot of it's thinking really critically 
about where do you play, and how do you win? 

261
00:23:28,520 --> 00:23:33,560
So being very selective about the markets you're 
in, and only being in markets where you can have  

262
00:23:33,560 --> 00:23:38,160
a leadership position. And then, being really 
crisp about what is your leadership position? And  

263
00:23:38,160 --> 00:23:45,600
so that was a very timely thing to read in terms 
of, "All right. Dropbox looks like one product,  

264
00:23:45,600 --> 00:23:50,280
but it's really participating in many different 
markets. And our big risk might be that we're  

265
00:23:50,280 --> 00:23:54,920
the number two best thing in each of those 
markets, which would be a bad situation." 

266
00:23:54,920 --> 00:24:02,520
Another really influential book was Only the 
Paranoid Survive by Andy Grove, and I'd been  

267
00:24:02,520 --> 00:24:08,360
a big fan of Andy's. High Output Management 
is another great book of his, which was my  

268
00:24:08,360 --> 00:24:13,440
introduction to management. At least, his theory 
of management. So just loved that book. And then  

269
00:24:13,440 --> 00:24:17,480
Only the Paranoid Survive talks about Intel's 
experience where they actually had something  

270
00:24:17,480 --> 00:24:24,560
like this happen that I wasn't aware of, and we 
all know Intel as the microprocessor company,  

271
00:24:24,560 --> 00:24:29,280
Intel Inside. At least in the 80s, 90s.
But before, they were in microprocessors.  

272
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:38,080
They sold memory, RAM. In the 70s, they were 
running into a situation where they were really  

273
00:24:38,080 --> 00:24:45,600
high growth, successful business selling memory. 
But then, they had these Japanese competitors that  

274
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:52,840
were just building memory faster, better, cheaper. 
Just on every dimension. And potentially, also,  

275
00:24:52,840 --> 00:24:57,680
things like anti-competitive things where 
the government might be subsidizing these  

276
00:24:57,680 --> 00:25:02,640
manufacturers. This feeling not only 
they might just be better at the game,  

277
00:25:02,640 --> 00:25:08,120
but there's also not a level playing field.
But meanwhile, you wouldn't see it in their  

278
00:25:08,120 --> 00:25:14,000
numbers. They're still growing. And just that 
there were these weird dissonant experiences  

279
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:18,640
where salespeople just suddenly have problems 
selling into accounts that used to be a slam dunk,  

280
00:25:18,640 --> 00:25:23,760
or things that used to work just stop 
working. And this happens. Blackberry's,  

281
00:25:23,760 --> 00:25:28,040
and Nokia's best sales years happened in the 
years after launching the iPhone. So these  

282
00:25:28,040 --> 00:25:34,680
things don't actually change immediately. And so 
Andy labeled these moments strategic inflection  

283
00:25:34,680 --> 00:25:39,760
points for a company, and I'm like, "Yeah. Then, 
we're definitely in a strategic inflection point." 

284
00:25:39,760 --> 00:25:43,520
But they were dealing with, "Oka., our whole 
business is memory. How do we deal with this  

285
00:25:43,520 --> 00:25:48,040
competition?" And there's this little vignette 
where he and Gordon Moore, one of the other  

286
00:25:48,040 --> 00:25:54,320
co-founders of Intel, said, "Hey, let's pretend 
we're consultants to ourselves. What would we  

287
00:25:54,320 --> 00:25:59,800
do?" And what they immediately decided was, "Oh, 
well, we clearly get out of the memory business,  

288
00:25:59,800 --> 00:26:04,160
and put all of our chips on this sketchy little 
microprocessor thing that was much smaller. But  

289
00:26:04,160 --> 00:26:10,600
very high growth, and potentially big market." And 
then they're like, "Well, why don't we do that?" 

290
00:26:10,600 --> 00:26:17,440
Only problem with that is it's like Google saying, 
"Yeah. Let's get out of search, and go all in on  

291
00:26:17,440 --> 00:26:25,440
Gmail, or something, or YouTube." So it just 
seemed insane. Andy cautions in the book that,  

292
00:26:25,440 --> 00:26:29,600
"Look, most of the time CEOs want options. They 
want to hedge their bets, but what you really  

293
00:26:29,600 --> 00:26:36,640
want to do in these strategic inflection points 
is go all in one thing." Or as Mark Twain put it,  

294
00:26:36,640 --> 00:26:42,920
"Put all your eggs in one basket, and watch 
that basket." And I was like, "All right. This  

295
00:26:42,920 --> 00:26:52,360
makes sense to me, but man, this is going to be 
painful." So we go away for 4th of July. I'm with  

296
00:26:52,360 --> 00:26:57,960
my family in New Hampshire. I reread the book, I 
come back. All right. I'm like, "Well, we really  

297
00:26:57,960 --> 00:27:01,713
got to do it." Then, I just killed Carousel, 
killed Mailbox. Went all in on productivity...

298
00:27:01,713 --> 00:27:06,400
Killed mailbox, went all in on productivity. 
To some extent, that was a relatively easy  

299
00:27:06,400 --> 00:27:11,760
decision because most of our subscribers, 80% of 
people paying for Dropbox were using it at work.  

300
00:27:11,760 --> 00:27:18,720
But that meant foreclosing on photo sharing and 
consumer and storage and all these things that  

301
00:27:18,720 --> 00:27:24,840
Dropbox had become synonymous with and to this day 
are some of the things that we're most recognized  

302
00:27:24,840 --> 00:27:30,440
for. And I wish I could say then everything 
got better. It was the opposite, actually,  

303
00:27:30,440 --> 00:27:35,160
the narrative completely flipped on the company. 
The press started, we killed these new products,  

304
00:27:35,160 --> 00:27:43,960
and then internally and externally, the narrative 
became super negative. Articles would come out  

305
00:27:43,960 --> 00:27:50,160
every week or two, like, oh, Dropbox could be the 
first dead deck of corn. And then sometimes we've  

306
00:27:50,160 --> 00:27:55,800
all seen this in tech companies get in this 
washing machine of self-perpetuating negative  

307
00:27:55,800 --> 00:28:01,960
press. And if it goes deep enough, I mean, Uber 
had this for a while later, Meta's had this over  

308
00:28:01,960 --> 00:28:06,720
their history, lots of companies where you 
just can't get the monkey off your back. 

309
00:28:06,720 --> 00:28:11,840
And then because what the reporters end up doing 
is they basically park their metaphorical van  

310
00:28:11,840 --> 00:28:16,640
behind your office. They interview all the people 
that you just fired and then print everything that  

311
00:28:16,640 --> 00:28:26,960
they say anonymously as if it were facts. And 
there's a lot of truth to what the press were  

312
00:28:26,960 --> 00:28:32,600
saying, so I can't really blame them or saying 
they were being unfair, but it immediately put  

313
00:28:32,600 --> 00:28:36,720
recruiting into this deep freeze. You're just 
in the situation. You've started this company,  

314
00:28:36,720 --> 00:28:41,840
it's been super successful, and then suddenly 
your employees don't want to wear your T-shirt  

315
00:28:41,840 --> 00:28:45,400
anymore. And frankly, you don't even want 
to wear your T-shirt anymore. It's just your  

316
00:28:46,760 --> 00:28:53,200
pride in your own company takes a big hit.
And meanwhile, I've talked mostly about the  

317
00:28:53,200 --> 00:29:00,440
external market competitive forces, but inside the 
company was a mess too. The business's revenue had  

318
00:29:00,440 --> 00:29:07,800
scaled so much faster than our ability to hire 
and build the right infrastructure and operations  

319
00:29:07,800 --> 00:29:12,960
internally. And so everybody's just panicking and 
being like, "All right, well good, Drew, we're not  

320
00:29:12,960 --> 00:29:18,560
doing Carousel, we're not doing Mailbox. What are 
we doing?" And the truth was like, if I knew the  

321
00:29:18,560 --> 00:29:24,320
answer to that, we would be doing it, but it's 
just this is going to take some time to figure  

322
00:29:24,320 --> 00:29:31,480
out. So it was pretty tough when everybody's 
looking to you as the founder and CEO looking for  

323
00:29:31,480 --> 00:29:36,560
quick fixes and answers, and also just wondering, 
how the hell did you get us in this situation?

324
00:29:36,560 --> 00:29:39,560
Wow. So we're going to talk about how you're  

325
00:29:39,560 --> 00:29:41,920
actually turning things around 
and the work you're doing now,  

326
00:29:41,920 --> 00:29:45,200
learning from this experience. But I have a lot 
of questions about this part of the journey.

327
00:29:45,200 --> 00:29:45,880
Yeah, yeah.

328
00:29:45,880 --> 00:29:51,160
Just to almost summarize the journey, 
it's like launch, killing it, viral,  

329
00:29:51,160 --> 00:29:55,000
find all these opportunities, find all these 
big markets. You start three different product  

330
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:59,760
lines. There's the enterprise use case, 
there's the consumer file storage use case,  

331
00:29:59,760 --> 00:30:05,720
there's photo sharing, there's productivity, and 
then basically every big incumbent's like, okay,  

332
00:30:05,720 --> 00:30:10,640
great, we're going to come eat your lunch. And 
you end up fighting wars on three or four fronts  

333
00:30:10,640 --> 00:30:17,760
against the big kahunas that have infinite cash 
and can do whatever they want. It's interesting  

334
00:30:17,760 --> 00:30:21,760
the way you described the Apple launch of just 
like it was this mushroom cloud you didn't quite  

335
00:30:21,760 --> 00:30:27,800
see for a while, but the Google Photos launch 
was like, okay, that was more clear of like,  

336
00:30:27,800 --> 00:30:31,560
okay, this is bad news. I know it's 
always easy in hindsight of like, oh,  

337
00:30:31,560 --> 00:30:34,680
I should have done something different 
when Apple launched this thing. But is  

338
00:30:34,680 --> 00:30:39,640
there anything maybe you could have done, or 
was it even possible to have adjusted course  

339
00:30:39,640 --> 00:30:44,880
at that point? Or was it like, okay, this 
is tough and we need time to figure it out?

340
00:30:44,880 --> 00:30:47,280
Well, we panicked about the Apple 
thing too, because that also,  

341
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:53,160
that created a much smaller version of the 
tempest in a teapot that the Google Photos  

342
00:30:53,160 --> 00:31:02,960
did. It was just much less public. Or it was just 
less obvious that we would be so out position.  

343
00:31:04,160 --> 00:31:11,480
And actually we were more surprised to the upside 
when it's Google Drive launches, iCloud launches,  

344
00:31:11,480 --> 00:31:17,760
OneDrive launches. And even as they build version 
two that we just didn't really notice that much of  

345
00:31:17,760 --> 00:31:26,920
a problem. And I also studied over the years 
what happened in Netscape and companies like  

346
00:31:26,920 --> 00:31:33,080
[inaudible 00:31:27] MySpace or these other 
cautionary tales. And interestingly, Internet  

347
00:31:33,080 --> 00:31:40,160
Explorer was a thing that eventually undermined 
Netscape enough to permanently throw it into a  

348
00:31:40,160 --> 00:31:46,160
negative trajectory. But Internet Explorer 1.0, 
2.0, even maybe 3.0 just weren't that good and  

349
00:31:46,160 --> 00:31:52,080
didn't really do anything but Internet Explorer 
4.0, 5.0 and all the bundling, that really made  

350
00:31:52,080 --> 00:31:57,840
a big difference, or big negative difference.
And then another thing that was interesting was,  

351
00:31:58,560 --> 00:32:03,600
so there's a big time lag where between when 
these products launch and when they actually  

352
00:32:03,600 --> 00:32:08,640
have an impact, because often it's not so much 
the existence of the product or it's availability,  

353
00:32:08,640 --> 00:32:15,400
it's the constant bundling or the constant 
iteration, or it's the boa constrictor,  

354
00:32:16,280 --> 00:32:24,120
in any given second, it's not much tighter, but 
over the following day, you're in a bad place. 

355
00:32:24,120 --> 00:32:28,040
But another thing that was interesting 
was one cool thing that we got to do  

356
00:32:28,040 --> 00:32:35,920
and moving to California is you get to actually 
meet people who had been at these companies. And  

357
00:32:35,920 --> 00:32:45,160
one of those people was a guy named Bill Campbell 
who was at Netscape during that whole period,  

358
00:32:45,160 --> 00:32:48,320
and I had asked him, I'm like, "Man, that's 
really unfair. That sucks what happened with  

359
00:32:48,320 --> 00:32:54,200
Microsoft and bundling with Windows and all these 
things and the antitrust and this and that." And  

360
00:32:54,200 --> 00:33:01,240
he's looked at me, he laughed at and snorted and 
he's like, "Microsoft did not kill us. We killed  

361
00:33:01,240 --> 00:33:12,480
ourselves." And so that was the other half of 
what was the problem within Dropbox was a lot  

362
00:33:12,480 --> 00:33:19,560
of our wounds were self-inflicted in that we were 
struggling to keep scaling and launching all these  

363
00:33:19,560 --> 00:33:29,800
products. And the Dropbox products had stagnated.
And I started to learn the hard way that, okay,  

364
00:33:29,800 --> 00:33:35,920
yeah, I now understand what Bill is talking about, 
because we were hiring all these smart people,  

365
00:33:35,920 --> 00:33:42,640
but the things we would do as a company would 
seem really stupid. And then some of these things  

366
00:33:42,640 --> 00:33:47,040
were me personally, like yeah, I knew about 
from reading all these different things, but  

367
00:33:47,040 --> 00:33:54,760
for whatever reason, I guess we just kept 
going anyhow. We were just too confident  

368
00:33:54,760 --> 00:34:00,200
in our ability to respond, or we got lulled 
into this complacency, we were like, " Oh,  

369
00:34:00,200 --> 00:34:03,760
well." Because it hasn't been a problem, 
it won't be a problem in the future. 

370
00:34:03,760 --> 00:34:09,320
But I'd say there's something about the Google 
Photos launch that just really set things off  

371
00:34:09,320 --> 00:34:17,880
kilter. And then also for me personally, I 
think, I'd go from feeling good but stressed  

372
00:34:17,880 --> 00:34:27,720
out all the time to mostly feeling bad all 
the time. And I just remember leaving, really  

373
00:34:28,280 --> 00:34:32,360
trying to get away from the office for a 
little bit during this period, picked my  

374
00:34:32,360 --> 00:34:37,080
teeth up off the ground. And the good news, I 
bought a place in Hawaii, so I was doing that  

375
00:34:37,080 --> 00:34:49,240
in Hawaii, but didn't feel very good in any way.
And then I learned. I had to really figure out  

376
00:34:49,240 --> 00:34:55,440
a lot of different things for myself to be the 
leader that could get us through this. Because  

377
00:34:55,440 --> 00:35:02,680
mostly what I felt was like, man, I felt like 
we'd been doing such a good job, but now, man,  

378
00:35:02,680 --> 00:35:13,000
if I really screw this up, or maybe I don't know 
what I'm doing. And then I had to really reset  

379
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:22,320
on a number of fronts. One is I just remember 
thinking my 18-year-old self would be like,  

380
00:35:22,320 --> 00:35:29,560
what the hell are you complaining about? You did 
it. This is so great, and yet I felt so bad about  

381
00:35:29,560 --> 00:35:38,040
things. And so I'm like, yeah, both of those 
things are true. How do I navigate that? And  

382
00:35:38,040 --> 00:35:43,880
I think one part that was really helpful is 
getting a sense of equanimity basically, and  

383
00:35:43,880 --> 00:35:50,160
doing a lot around mindfulness and meditation to 
distance... One thing that happens when you're a  

384
00:35:50,160 --> 00:35:57,640
founder and your company succeeds is your identity 
is fused with the company. And so it's easy to get  

385
00:35:57,640 --> 00:36:03,200
into a situation where you only feel good if the 
company's... Or how you feel is how the company is  

386
00:36:03,200 --> 00:36:11,800
doing, and you need to separate that a little bit. 
So what that looked like for me is recognizing,  

387
00:36:11,800 --> 00:36:20,360
yeah, there's really not an easy button that keeps 
things up and to the right forever. And most of  

388
00:36:20,360 --> 00:36:25,600
the entrepreneurs that are my heroes had various 
periods of wandering in the desert. Those things  

389
00:36:25,600 --> 00:36:31,160
instead of just being problems were probably the 
crucible that forged the people that they became.  

390
00:36:31,160 --> 00:36:38,160
So the presence of badness is not necessarily 
you are bad. And it's like, yeah, now you're  

391
00:36:38,160 --> 00:36:43,000
just getting your stripes as an entrepreneur.
And people were really helpful during that  

392
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:48,400
period. So I mentioned Bill Campbell. He was 
nice enough that we just stayed in touch and he  

393
00:36:48,400 --> 00:36:53,560
would take me out to dinner every now and then. 
And I would be freaking out, but I was always  

394
00:36:53,560 --> 00:36:58,360
