And mostly he'd just be saying like, all right,  

395
00:36:58,360 --> 00:37:04,640
he'd dust you off and smack you and say, get 
your ass back out there. And he was literally  

396
00:37:04,640 --> 00:37:12,720
a coach of the Columbia football team in addition 
to being a great technology executive and advisor  

397
00:37:12,720 --> 00:37:20,400
to many of the great founders that I looked up 
to. He was really helpful because he helped me  

398
00:37:20,400 --> 00:37:26,480
believe in myself even when I wouldn't believe 
in myself. And then people like Andy Grove who  

399
00:37:26,480 --> 00:37:31,680
had written all these books, I'm like, well, at 
least I'm having this problem. But yeah, then that  

400
00:37:31,680 --> 00:37:35,480
raised a question for me. I'm like, okay, I've 
been through this chapter one where everything's  

401
00:37:35,480 --> 00:37:46,560
up and to the right, but I ran out of merit badges 
or Xbox achievements to collect. I was like,  

402
00:37:47,560 --> 00:37:54,040
we did it. We got the product to this many users, 
we got it to where we got this valuation, or let  

403
00:37:54,040 --> 00:38:01,160
me back up. So my whole life, or it's common, I 
think for a lot of founders, especially if you get  

404
00:38:01,160 --> 00:38:07,760
good grades and stuff, you follow pretty linear 
path from childhood, from first get the right  

405
00:38:07,760 --> 00:38:11,440
test scores, then get into the right college, get 
into the right college, take the right classes,  

406
00:38:11,440 --> 00:38:16,840
get the right internship, get the right job. And 
early startup life is like that a lot. It's like,  

407
00:38:16,840 --> 00:38:22,280
okay, have an idea. Find a co-founder, get 
into Y Combinator, get funding from Sequoia. 

408
00:38:22,280 --> 00:38:27,440
Watch an MVP just in 10 million, a 
hundred million, billion valuation.  

409
00:38:27,960 --> 00:38:30,960
And I felt like we'd cleared all that. And 
so actually one of the other problems was,  

410
00:38:30,960 --> 00:38:37,040
I don't even know what Dropbox needs to be and 
I don't even know what I need that I want to  

411
00:38:37,040 --> 00:38:46,080
be in the world. And so part of this was also 
reconnecting to some kind of sense of purpose,  

412
00:38:46,080 --> 00:38:49,640
because if I was really honest with myself, 
I was like, well, I'm just checking boxes and  

413
00:38:49,640 --> 00:38:54,080
advancing and leveling up like a video game or 
something, but now I'm here. I'm like, all right,  

414
00:38:54,080 --> 00:38:59,720
is it just big numbers bigger? It's also not that 
fun to just launch something that you put your  

415
00:38:59,720 --> 00:39:03,640
soul into and then just have it get crushed with 
these competitors. It's even worse when you're  

416
00:39:03,640 --> 00:39:09,840
