417
00:39:10,520 --> 00:39:18,240
So are we just inventing things 10 minutes 
before Google and Apple do? If not,  

418
00:39:18,240 --> 00:39:23,040
what are we doing? And then if we're really, 
really honest with ourselves, I think it's hard  

419
00:39:23,040 --> 00:39:29,600
to argue that no one would've invented cloud 
photo gallery that wasn't constrained to your  

420
00:39:29,600 --> 00:39:37,120
local storage. So I had to really rethink what 
does the company need to do. That actually took  

421
00:39:37,120 --> 00:39:43,040
a longer time to answer than I wanted, but then 
also just what do I want to do? And I was like,  

422
00:39:43,040 --> 00:39:49,000
well, you know what? I'm going to do this.
What I ended up settling on was like, look,  

423
00:39:50,040 --> 00:39:55,080
coming back to my 18-year-old self, I was like, 
all right, stop complaining. This is a pretty  

424
00:39:55,080 --> 00:40:00,280
good situation. You wanted something where the 
learning curve would be steep. Here it is. You  

425
00:40:00,280 --> 00:40:04,240
get to do this really meaningful work to build 
things for millions of people, work with awesome  

426
00:40:05,720 --> 00:40:10,440
teammates. There's always good things about it, 
and you've chosen this life, so stop complaining  

427
00:40:10,440 --> 00:40:16,520
about the burdens because it's really dangerous if 
you start to resent the job or feel like a victim  

428
00:40:16,520 --> 00:40:20,480
because that's just corrosive to everything 
else that you can get in this spin cycle.

429
00:40:20,480 --> 00:40:25,480
What helped you come to that place? Because 
that sounds like a very hard place to get to  

430
00:40:25,480 --> 00:40:29,960
and a very important place. Was that Bill 
Campbell advice? How long did it take you  

431
00:40:29,960 --> 00:40:35,680
to go from this is not going well and life 
sucks to, okay, let's look at it this way?

432
00:40:35,680 --> 00:40:40,120
I think there were a couple unlocks that were 
pretty fast, but I think again, this was not like,  

433
00:40:40,120 --> 00:40:47,720
oh, then I felt better and we lived happily 
ever after at all. There were some moments  

434
00:40:47,720 --> 00:40:55,080
of recognition where I was able to, I always try 
to get away from the mayhem or the whirlwind and  

435
00:40:55,080 --> 00:41:01,680
recenter myself and do think weeks and things like 
that. And so those were really helpful because  

436
00:41:01,680 --> 00:41:07,640
I felt when I diagnosed, well, when I'm on this 
treadmill and just firefighting or how did I miss  

437
00:41:07,640 --> 00:41:15,720
this important thing? It's like, well, basically 
the root causes of being on the treadmills,  

438
00:41:15,720 --> 00:41:21,880
I was too busy firing to aim, and then I 
thought I would do my aiming on vacations and  

439
00:41:21,880 --> 00:41:28,960
things like that. But no, I need to get off the 
treadmill every now and then and make the space  

440
00:41:28,960 --> 00:41:33,360
to really address some of these bigger questions.
Because it's not like I didn't forget about them.  

441
00:41:33,360 --> 00:41:40,280
They just were always below the fold on my to-do 
list to deal with. And then until a few years go  

442
00:41:40,280 --> 00:41:44,920
by and you're like, wait. Yeah, we really were 
just strategically out of position. The other  

443
00:41:44,920 --> 00:41:51,560
way I came to some of these conclusions is a 
combination of things. So I think picking up  

444
00:41:51,560 --> 00:41:58,320
a meditation or mindfulness practice, having 
therapists personally, having coaches, having  

445
00:41:58,320 --> 00:42:02,920
friends and mentors, other founder friends. And so 
I wouldn't say it was any one thing, but I think  

446
00:42:03,440 --> 00:42:07,920
you have to build this whole ecosystem of support 
around yourself and recognize no one's going to  

447
00:42:07,920 --> 00:42:13,640
do that for you. And it's super important.
And then to Bill's other point, he was like,  

448
00:42:13,640 --> 00:42:19,400
yeah, Microsoft wasn't killing us, we were 
killing ourselves, I think having to ask some  

449
00:42:19,400 --> 00:42:27,400
hard questions to myself of, yeah, some of these 
wounds were self-inflicted. As much as there might  

450
00:42:27,400 --> 00:42:32,640
be, I could look at this and say, oh, Microsoft 
is mean, or Google was mean, or Apple was mean,  

451
00:42:32,640 --> 00:42:40,720
but I'm like, I drove the ship towards these 
rocks. So that's one downside of being founder,  

452
00:42:40,720 --> 00:42:47,080
CEO. You can't blame the last guy. I think 
one of the big questions every founder  

453
00:42:47,080 --> 00:42:52,520
