weaknesses are massively amplified and a lot  

456
00:43:04,680 --> 00:43:10,600
of blind spots in your personality can become 
huge cultural dysfunctions in the company.  

457
00:43:10,600 --> 00:43:17,200
And so step one to dealing with that is building 
awareness. And one thing that floated around the  

458
00:43:17,200 --> 00:43:23,720
company for a while was the Enneagram, which 
on the surface is a personality typing thing  

459
00:43:23,720 --> 00:43:32,320
like Myers-Briggs. I often describe it as it's 
like Myers-Briggs, but actually useful. The way  

460
00:43:32,320 --> 00:43:37,000
it works is it's a personality typing system. 
You get a number from one through nine that's  

461
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:43,440
your dominant... Or there's nine types that are 
numbered. It's similar to Myers-Briggs in that  

462
00:43:43,440 --> 00:43:50,120
Myers-Briggs has 16 types of letters like ENFJ or 
different things. But I find that Myers-Briggs is  

463
00:43:50,120 --> 00:43:56,000
more descriptive. So it tells you, okay, you're 
an introvert, not an extrovert or vice versa.  

464
00:43:56,000 --> 00:44:02,720
You're judging instead of perceiving. But I could 
never really work out what that meant. And so  

465
00:44:02,720 --> 00:44:10,600
it's descriptive versus predictive or causal.
Enneagram I find is the theory that is really  

466
00:44:10,600 --> 00:44:14,480
about your fundamental motivations. What are you 
running towards and what are you running away  

467
00:44:14,480 --> 00:44:20,040
from? And the theory goes through some combination 
of your wiring from your genetics and your early  

468
00:44:20,040 --> 00:44:30,360
childhood. Your autopilot is fixed after your 
childhood in that you just have instinctive  

469
00:44:30,360 --> 00:44:34,520
responses to things. Now it's autopilot. It 
doesn't mean it's your destiny. You could override  

470
00:44:34,520 --> 00:44:42,320
it, but it's super important to become aware of 
what are you running from and towards. And the  

471
00:44:42,320 --> 00:44:49,800
Enneagram gives you a really good map to do that.
And so I'm reading this book and it starts by you  

472
00:44:49,800 --> 00:44:55,280
type yourself, and I'm rolling my eyes. I'm 
like, okay, I'm a seven. What's a seven? And  

473
00:44:55,280 --> 00:45:00,920
then you read, each type has its own chapter and 
you read the chapter and I was like, oh my God,  

474
00:45:00,920 --> 00:45:07,240
this completely describes who I am down to 
my core. And I was almost looking over my  

475
00:45:07,240 --> 00:45:13,400
shoulder. Who the hell did this? I thought I was 
a special snowflake, but apparently not. Okay,  

476
00:45:13,400 --> 00:45:19,120
I'm listening. And [inaudible 00:45:16] with a 
lot of my early coaching experiences, which are,  

477
00:45:19,120 --> 00:45:24,840
you do a 360, your coach sits you down, 
they're like, here are your strengths. In  

478
00:45:24,840 --> 00:45:29,320
my case, it would be things like, oh, you're 
really creative and you like new ideas. That's  

479
00:45:29,320 --> 00:45:34,760
okay. And second, you really love people. You 
build great relationships with people. I'm like,  

480
00:45:34,760 --> 00:45:41,360
okay. Uh-huh. Third, you're really comfortable 
in chaos and resilient. I was like, this coaching  

481
00:45:41,360 --> 00:45:45,480
thing is great. See, yeah, that was my first 
coach. And then you flip to your development  

482
00:45:45,480 --> 00:45:52,840
areas because no one calls them weaknesses.
It's like, all right, one is you're bored by  

483
00:45:52,840 --> 00:46:02,320
routine and really undisciplined. Second is 
you're really conflict avoidant. And third is  

484
00:46:05,080 --> 00:46:09,360
you're intuitive, but you're also pretty chaotic 
and don't create enough structure for people  

485
00:46:09,360 --> 00:46:15,680
so they're mostly confused. And when you pair 
the two together, you're like, oh, wait. Yeah,  

486
00:46:15,680 --> 00:46:22,000
I'm creative and like new ideas, but I'm bored by 
routine and I'm a bit of a space cadet. All right,  

487
00:46:23,520 --> 00:46:26,320
you love good relationships with people, but 
you don't want to make them unhappy so you  

488
00:46:26,320 --> 00:46:32,920
don't tell them the truth basically about things 
that are difficult to hear. And it's going to be  

489
00:46:32,920 --> 00:46:37,200
a similar map of things depending on your 
personality type or circumstances. But the  

490
00:46:37,200 --> 00:46:42,640
Enneagram was that map for me to be like, okay, 
I've got these things that are genuinely great,  

491
00:46:42,640 --> 00:46:48,000
but I need to address these downsides 
of the company's conflict avoidant,  

492
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:52,960
so we're not telling the truth and then making 
a bunch of predictable mistakes, or I'm creating  

493
00:46:52,960 --> 00:46:57,000
this really chaotic environment where people 
don't know what they're supposed to be doing. 

494
00:46:57,000 --> 00:47:01,760
That's a problem. My personality is quite 
directly, I'm going to torpedo the company  

495
00:47:01,760 --> 00:47:07,360
unless I do something about it. The same is 
true for any founder. And I'm a type seven,  

496
00:47:07,360 --> 00:47:13,360
it's the enthusiast. It's like, again, central 
casting is like a lot of new things and creative  

497
00:47:13,360 --> 00:47:20,720
and love just interesting things. But then a 
space cadet, FOMO, some of the shadow side of it,  

498
00:47:20,720 --> 00:47:25,240
and every type has a thing like that. 
So really understanding, okay then,  

499
00:47:25,240 --> 00:47:29,160
I was also just frustrated in the day-to-day of my 
work, I'm like, yeah, I'm not really getting to do  

500
00:47:29,160 --> 00:47:37,480
these creative things where I'm too busy firing to 
aim. I'm missing these bigger picture things that  

501
00:47:37,480 --> 00:47:43,440
are really taking the ship way too close to the 
rocks. Okay. Then I need to then understand what  

502
00:47:43,440 --> 00:47:49,960
those things are and either work on myself or hire 
the right people who don't have those issues or  

503
00:47:49,960 --> 00:47:55,960
one way or another, just make it so the company 
is not so exposed to my personal dysfunction. 

504
00:47:55,960 --> 00:47:59,680
And so yeah, it was a whole constellation of 
things like that where it's like, all right,  

505
00:47:59,680 --> 00:48:05,040
we have to get... I mean, after this whole 
tailspin, we got to work. I'm like, all right,  

506
00:48:05,040 --> 00:48:11,600
first business issues. The most urgent issues 
were just blowing all this cash. We need to get  

507
00:48:11,600 --> 00:48:18,000
