and that set the tracks for getting into a  

511
00:48:34,600 --> 00:48:42,440
billion run rate in 2017, going public in 2018.
We had to come up with a new vision and mission  

512
00:48:42,440 --> 00:48:47,760
for the company, which I'll maybe save 
for chapter three. And then I was also  

513
00:48:47,760 --> 00:48:54,080
just trying to do things that helped sustain me 
through the difficult things. I'm like, well,  

514
00:48:54,080 --> 00:48:59,600
I am an engineer. As a little kid, I was coding 
since childhood. I knew I wanted be a founder.  

515
00:48:59,600 --> 00:49:06,160
I didn't know I wanted be a CEO, so I backed 
into being a CEO. And then, so I'm like, man,  

516
00:49:06,720 --> 00:49:12,480
there's a lot of tedious things about being an 
executive. So I was like, I'm going to find ways  

517
00:49:12,480 --> 00:49:17,720
to automate tedious parts of my job and learn 
machine learning in 2016 and '17, and that ended  

518
00:49:17,720 --> 00:49:23,400
up being really important later on. But then also 
it's just coming to terms with my job and what I  

519
00:49:23,400 --> 00:49:28,960
wanted to do from a personal perspective, which 
included things like, oh, I'm lucky in that being  

520
00:49:28,960 --> 00:49:36,720
a CEO is, I always wanted a steep learning curve.
In a lot of professions like in sports or math or  

521
00:49:36,720 --> 00:49:43,080
chess or certain academic fields, you peak in your 
twenties or thirties. CEO's not like that. You can  

522
00:49:43,080 --> 00:49:48,600
go your whole life and still not be a master. So 
I'm like, for better or worse, it's pretty cool  

523
00:49:48,600 --> 00:49:55,360
that I can do this kind of work. And then I don't 
really get that much out of just chasing bigger  

524
00:49:55,360 --> 00:50:00,800
numbers. The thing that is my favorite thing 
about Dropbox is looking over someone's shoulder  

525
00:50:00,800 --> 00:50:06,520
in Starbucks and seeing if the little Dropbox icon 
is there. Building something that becomes a verb,  

526
00:50:06,520 --> 00:50:12,600
taking some of the pain out of technology, things 
like that. So really reorienting. Yeah, it's not  

527
00:50:12,600 --> 00:50:19,000
about just the external scoreboard just much. 
It's more about the craft of being a great CEO  

528
00:50:19,560 --> 00:50:25,440
and building things I'm really proud of or really 
making a difference. And so those kinds of things,  

529
00:50:25,440 --> 00:50:31,600
none of them all coalesce. It's like this lens 
that slowly and stubbornly comes into focus,  

530
00:50:31,600 --> 00:50:35,960
but making the time to have some of 
that reflection was super important.

531
00:50:35,960 --> 00:50:41,040
So much of what you're describing makes me think 
about founder mode in a lot of different ways. One  

532
00:50:41,040 --> 00:50:46,080
is your point about how you didn't have a lot of 
time to think about where things might be going  

533
00:50:46,080 --> 00:50:50,960
and how the markets are shifting, and that has 
to happen, basically, no one else is going to  

534
00:50:50,960 --> 00:50:56,880
do that if it's not you. Also, just this idea of 
how much of the solution was you understanding  

535
00:50:56,880 --> 00:51:01,520
yourself better, reflecting on where you have 
strengths and weaknesses. Also, I'll mention,  

536
00:51:01,520 --> 00:51:05,240
so before I had Brian Chesky on the podcast, I 
