with a lot of benefits. It really works. The  

715
01:08:49,840 --> 01:08:55,800
employee retention, satisfaction, engagement 
or offer separates all the things we care about  

716
01:08:55,800 --> 01:09:01,760
have been significantly up since COVID. There's 
many factors to that, but there's a lot that's  

717
01:09:01,760 --> 01:09:06,120
working about the model. But really, we're 
approaching it from a product standpoint. 

718
01:09:07,040 --> 01:09:11,640
In deciding to turn Dropbox into this lab 
for distributed work, we're like, "Okay,  

719
01:09:11,640 --> 01:09:16,840
when you open up your laptop in 2025, 2030, what 
do you see?" Hopefully, there's some new stuff  

720
01:09:16,840 --> 01:09:20,600
or some things that are different on there. What 
are those things, and how do we bring them back? 

721
01:09:20,600 --> 01:09:25,720
One of the first things you lose when you 
go distributed is context. We get a lot.  

722
01:09:25,720 --> 01:09:30,320
You get a lot for free from osmosis. Just, "Oh, 
hey, how are you doing? How's this?" Or, "Oh,  

723
01:09:30,320 --> 01:09:34,400
do you have that thing?" But then when 
you're remote, then a lot of that gets  

724
01:09:34,400 --> 01:09:39,720
replaced with endless video meetings, and lots 
of Slack messages, which is super inefficient. 

725
01:09:41,680 --> 01:09:46,880
Also, one thing that was clear across the board 
from all the successful remote first companies  

726
01:09:46,880 --> 01:09:54,200
was you have to be more documented, but then you 
have a lot more documents. This started turning  

727
01:09:54,200 --> 01:09:59,040
up very obvious problems, which is like, 
"Wait, why do I have 1 search box at home,  

728
01:09:59,040 --> 01:10:03,600
and 10 search boxes at work? Why is it easier to 
search all of human knowledge than my company's  

729
01:10:03,600 --> 01:10:08,200
knowledge? Why is this problem getting worse 
not better every year?" If you think about it,  

730
01:10:08,200 --> 01:10:13,040
we've got 10 search boxes that you search 10% of 
our stuff. I'm like, "We should just fix this." 

731
01:10:14,120 --> 01:10:19,520
Again, even just as a frustrated user, maybe 2018, 
2019, I'm having this problem myself. I'm like,  

732
01:10:19,520 --> 01:10:23,640
"It's really hard to find stuff." Plus 
there's always cool vector search stuff,  

733
01:10:23,640 --> 01:10:28,080
and deep learning stuff happening. Even 
for ChatGPT, I'm going to make a personal  

734
01:10:28,080 --> 01:10:32,320
search engine that takes us, so I shouldn't 
have to, right? If I search for strategy,  

735
01:10:32,320 --> 01:10:37,440
and the title of the document is plan, it 
should get it right, and the matching should  

736
01:10:37,440 --> 01:10:42,040
be fuzzy. Then I built something like this. 
I'm like, "Oh my God, it completely works."

737
01:10:42,560 --> 01:10:44,280
You built this yourself, you're saying?

738
01:10:44,280 --> 01:10:50,800
Yeah, it went nowhere for a couple of years, 
but then after COVID, and after we're dealing  

739
01:10:50,800 --> 01:10:54,240
with all these information problems, I'm like, 
"Yeah, we should be the company that helps you  

740
01:10:54,240 --> 01:10:58,920
get the right information at the right 
time to the right person." I built that  

741
01:10:58,920 --> 01:11:07,120
little hacked up search engine thing that 
I made, might be an ingredient to this. 

742
01:11:07,800 --> 01:11:11,040
We bought a little company called Command E that 
was doing universal search, and we created this  

743
01:11:11,040 --> 01:11:17,040
new product called Dropbox Dash. Basically, Dash 
connects to all your different apps. It gives you  

744
01:11:17,040 --> 01:11:23,480
universal search. Then obviously after ChatGPT, 
not only can you do conventional search, but you  

745
01:11:23,480 --> 01:11:28,040
can ask questions in natural language, and answer 
a lot of the questions that ChatGPT can't because  

746
01:11:28,040 --> 01:11:36,200
it's not connected to your stuff. If you ask 
ChatGPT like, "When does my lease expire? Where's  

747
01:11:36,200 --> 01:11:41,800
that slide from last year's product launch," can't 
tell you because it's not personalized. Because  

748
01:11:41,800 --> 01:11:48,320
it's not connected to your information. We did all 
of that for this whole connector platform where we  

749
01:11:48,320 --> 01:11:53,200
index the known universe of SaaS apps, have this 
kind of intelligence engine that brings all of it  

750
01:11:53,200 --> 01:11:57,800
into a common representation, and lets you do 
conventional search, natural language search. 

751
01:11:58,720 --> 01:12:04,680
Then more than that, we want to organize your 
working life for you. Stepping back even further,  

752
01:12:05,560 --> 01:12:10,800
often it happens that a company likes to starts 
solving a problem, and that problem is never  

753
01:12:10,800 --> 01:12:19,320
permanently solved. In a lot of ways, Dash is 
the biggest, best embodiment of solving the same  

754
01:12:19,320 --> 01:12:22,840
kinds of problems I started Dropbox to begin 
with. Because on the one hand, I was talking  

755
01:12:22,840 --> 01:12:27,480
about thumb drive, but I wasn't, really. If you 
think about the higher level job to be done,  

756
01:12:27,480 --> 01:12:34,520
I was like, "No, the real issue is that it's 
super hard to find my stuff, organize my stuff,  

757
01:12:34,520 --> 01:12:38,000
share my stuff, and secure my stuff."
In the beginning that was like my stuff  

758
01:12:38,000 --> 01:12:44,040
was my files, and the scattering was across 
devices. Now, the stuff is tabs in my browser,  

759
01:12:44,040 --> 01:12:48,440
and cloud tools. But it's a lot of the same 
problems. We've talked a lot about search,  

760
01:12:48,440 --> 01:12:57,080
but then organize is still a big problem. There's 
no desktop folder or desktop as in the physical  

761
01:12:57,080 --> 01:13:03,160
realm, when you're in your browser. It's just this 
ocean of content that washes by you. Then you get  

762
01:13:03,160 --> 01:13:08,880
tired. You nuke the whole environment. But there's 
nothing to come back to. There's no collection  

763
01:13:08,880 --> 01:13:15,280
concept. Files have folders, songs have playlists, 
links have ... If you're getting ready for board  

764
01:13:15,280 --> 01:13:22,080
meeting or remodeling a house, there's no common 
container. If you have a Google doc, and a 10 gig,  

765
01:13:22,080 --> 01:13:27,360
4K video, and an air table, this is a new problem.
Dash also has this thing called Stacks,  

766
01:13:27,360 --> 01:13:32,000
and has basically smart collections that 
helps make sharing a lot easier. But again,  

767
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:35,840
a lot of this was an intersection of like, 
"Yeah, how has work changed since COVID?  

768
01:13:35,840 --> 01:13:43,640
What crazy little science projects have I done? 
Then how should one find, organize, and share  

769
01:13:43,640 --> 01:13:49,280
their information in the cloud era? If I were to 
build Dropbox today, what would it look like?"  

770
01:13:49,280 --> 01:13:56,840
Dash is first part of the answer. We're super 
excited. But we just launched it two months ago,  

771
01:13:57,560 --> 01:14:06,600
and signed up our first customers. Then I can come 
back to just rebooting the core business too. I  

772
01:14:06,600 --> 01:14:14,560
think one of the big challenges or lessons from 
this whole period is that one, is as part of the  

773
01:14:14,560 --> 01:14:20,520
problem we had with competition, and this chapter 
two was external, but a lot of it was internal,  

774
01:14:20,520 --> 01:14:28,120
where we couldn't organize ourselves effectively. 
The business has scaled so much faster than our  

775
01:14:28,120 --> 01:14:36,200
ability to manage it. First is to recognize 
this is not an unusual problem. Many companies,  

776
01:14:36,200 --> 01:14:42,880
not all, but certainly many, and actually many in 
SaaS productivity have this sophomore slump where  

777
01:14:42,880 --> 01:14:49,360
you have the super successful first product, 
but then it's challenging to build the next  

778
01:14:49,360 --> 01:14:57,920
platinum album. Dropbox has fallen into that 
category. You could say Zoom, Slack, others. 

779
01:14:57,920 --> 01:15:06,920
First, it's easy to feel bad about it yourself, 
but no, you're not. This is actually a very  

780
01:15:06,920 --> 01:15:13,600
common problem. Then there's a lot of solutions. 
People devise lots of solutions to this. Part of  

781
01:15:13,600 --> 01:15:21,640
it's structural. Your company has to go from 
a pretty fun, and stable state of a functional  

782
01:15:21,640 --> 01:15:25,360
organization where you have engineering 
in product design, there's one product,  

783
01:15:25,360 --> 01:15:29,120
and there's one customer. Everybody's working, 
we are all in the same direction for the same  

784
01:15:29,120 --> 01:15:35,600
team to then when you have multiple products, 
then you have all these conflicts. How much  

785
01:15:35,600 --> 01:15:41,480
should we invest in the core business versus 
the new thing? Who should have authority in the  

786
01:15:41,480 --> 01:15:50,400
company? You try to build multiple products in a 
functional org, but then you lose accountability. 

787
01:15:50,400 --> 01:15:53,560
People are like, "I'm spending a lot. 
I'm trying to make Dropbox work. I'm  

788
01:15:53,560 --> 01:15:57,760
trying to make mailbox work. I'm trying 
to make paperwork, and all these things."  

789
01:15:59,920 --> 01:16:07,240
Then you respond by breaking up into groups or 
business units. We have a product business unit,  

790
01:16:07,240 --> 01:16:12,520
product GM structure. Then you have to refactor 
things to have a common technical platform, and  

791
01:16:12,520 --> 01:16:21,520
all the GNA functions. There's this metamorphosis, 
and maturation you need to go through that is mega  

792
01:16:21,520 --> 01:16:27,080
obvious to experienced people. That you're just 
totally blindsided by this if you're solving it  

793
01:16:27,080 --> 01:16:31,560
by trial and error. There's a great book, 
Zone to Win, that talks about some of this,  

794
01:16:31,560 --> 01:16:37,840
what needs to happen internally by Geoffrey Moore.
Then there's a lot of cultural problems that set  

795
01:16:37,840 --> 01:16:43,280
in. We just touched on some of them at a high 
level. But whether you're in a company or an  

796
01:16:43,280 --> 01:16:48,480
empire, a civilization, what gets you to the 
top turns out to be pretty similar things. You  

797
01:16:48,480 --> 01:16:55,040
have this outsider, challenger mentality 
where you have to eat what you kill, and  

798
01:16:55,040 --> 01:17:00,680
the odds are against you. Through hard work, 
learning, and grinding, you start moving up the  

799
01:17:00,680 --> 01:17:07,320
curve faster. But then once you're successful, 
then there's a temptation to take the foot off  

800
01:17:07,320 --> 01:17:13,880
the gas or enjoy the finer things in life or just 
focus on other things, be it other than what got  

801
01:17:13,880 --> 01:17:20,200
you there. I think what we experienced, many other 
companies experienced, Bill Campbell experienced  

802
01:17:20,200 --> 01:17:28,360
in Netscape, the success plants, the seeds of 
failure in terms of complacency, entitlements,  

803
01:17:28,360 --> 01:17:34,280
or taking your eye off of what got you to be 
successful in the first place, yeah, I went from  

804
01:17:34,280 --> 01:17:40,360
earning a lot of the early stage startup founder 
merit badges to earning the stagnation, and  

805
01:17:40,360 --> 01:17:47,840
irrelevance merit badge. Now, the turnaround merit 
badge. Part of that is the turnaround playbook. 

806
01:17:47,840 --> 01:17:52,880
Okay, first, it's just getting out of this 
delusional state where you think you're great,  

807
01:17:54,080 --> 01:17:58,760
just splashing cold water on everyone, and 
be like, "Look, we haven't shipped any. Last  

808
01:17:58,760 --> 01:18:03,000
three years, the only thing our customers have 
really meaningfully seen from our product is a  

809
01:18:03,000 --> 01:18:10,200
price increase. What the hell are we doing?"
A lot of it is getting back to like, "Hey,  

810
01:18:10,200 --> 01:18:17,480
we have to focus on craft. We have to embrace 
a growth mindset and learning. We have to stop  

811
01:18:17,480 --> 01:18:24,320
blaming external factors or displacing blame. 
We have to be a high agency culture." There's  

812
01:18:24,320 --> 01:18:29,520
a cultural transformation that you have 
to personally embody, and be clear about. 

813
01:18:29,520 --> 01:18:35,120
Then in our case, we had to reboot the whole 
exec team. We've had all the time getting  

814
01:18:35,120 --> 01:18:42,920
the right kind of leadership team in place for 
the end of chapter two and three. Part of what  

815
01:18:42,920 --> 01:18:49,000
happens in conjunction with a lot of the cultural 
stuff I just talked about, is also you can have  

816
01:18:49,000 --> 01:18:54,880
this as the talent flywheels flying forward, and 
flies in reverse. You have a new set of issues  

817
01:18:54,880 --> 01:19:00,240
where you get all these amazing people in the 
company, but they want to work for Facebook,  

818
01:19:00,240 --> 01:19:06,720
not MySpace. You start having retention problems 
when the narrative goes negative. We start  

819
01:19:06,720 --> 01:19:13,600
bleeding talents, and then it's also really hard 
to hire people for the same reasons. Especially,  

820
01:19:13,600 --> 01:19:18,000
as I think about where the big lessons from 
chapter two that we've addressed in chapter three,  

821
01:19:18,000 --> 01:19:28,000
the seniority gap is something that can accumulate 
because much of the talent can fly to the next  

822
01:19:28,000 --> 01:19:35,920
shiny thing. What you do in response typically 
is, you promote a lot of people internally,  

823
01:19:35,920 --> 01:19:41,200
which is good for them. It seems good for them in 
the short term, because they're just getting a lot  

824
01:19:41,200 --> 01:19:46,840
more authority, and responsibility quickly. People 
like that on day one. But it's a problem because  

825
01:19:46,840 --> 01:19:51,640
suddenly people are solving problems through trial 
and error. Things may be new to them that are not  

826
01:19:51,640 --> 01:19:58,560
new to the industry, and suddenly no knowns to the 
industry are unknown and knowns to those leaders.  

827
01:19:59,120 --> 01:20:07,280
Then usually you can get around that by hiring 
a layer of experienced execs or having enough of  

828
01:20:07,280 --> 01:20:13,920
them in the company. But in the talent wars of the 
late teens, we were in the situation as were many  

829
01:20:13,920 --> 01:20:20,400
companies where, any exec you talked to with any 
experience had five offers from fan companies for  

830
01:20:20,400 --> 01:20:28,160
three times the comp, and a third of the workload, 
or 10 offers from pre-IPO startups, and C-level  

831
01:20:28,160 --> 01:20:33,960
roles. These are offers in hand. The only thing 
that really worked to even just keep the lights on  

832
01:20:33,960 --> 01:20:40,360
was basically giving people double promotions so 
that they could justify someone who's a director  

833
01:20:40,360 --> 01:20:45,960
at company X, making him a VP at Dropbox. Then 
you had to do that because they literally had  

834
01:20:45,960 --> 01:20:52,280
offers in hand of many millions of dollars a year. 
Otherwise, you'd just hire no one. That cooled off  

835
01:20:52,280 --> 01:20:57,280
a lot after the correction in SaaS, after we 
got more of our vision straight, and certainly  

836
01:20:57,280 --> 01:21:03,280
after we've been working on things like Dash.
But that seniority gap is really rough. Where ...

837
01:21:04,240 --> 01:21:09,440
Seniority gap is really rough where you need to 
have enough experienced people in the company  

838
01:21:09,440 --> 01:21:13,160
who can then train your high potential 
people. And again, that sounds obvious,  

839
01:21:13,160 --> 01:21:17,920
but it's very difficult to do that in an 
environment where the talent flywheel is  

840
01:21:17,920 --> 01:21:21,200
going in your direction and then starts 
flying away from you really quickly. And  

841
01:21:21,200 --> 01:21:25,680
then through the battlefield promotions 
and these double promotions on hiring,  

842
01:21:25,680 --> 01:21:33,120
you can end up a situation where there's 
a huge voltage drop in terms of people's  

843
01:21:33,120 --> 01:21:40,920
matching between what your company needs and what 
they know how to do. And that also doesn't mean  

844
01:21:40,920 --> 01:21:48,000
hire only experienced people either because then 
you're splicing in a lot of outside DNA into your  

845
01:21:48,000 --> 01:21:56,200
organism. But what you want is to keep it roughly 
in balance. I mean 60-40, 40-60, 50-50, whatever.  

846
01:21:56,200 --> 01:22:00,640
But your high potential people also lose out if 
they don't have experienced people learning from. 

847
01:22:00,640 --> 01:22:07,480
So that's a little bit, I think that it was a big 
part of the stagnation. Again, it's not because  

848
01:22:07,480 --> 01:22:13,080
the people, but this was something that I was 
doing to my team. So it's not them or certainly on  

849
01:22:13,080 --> 01:22:18,360
my watch, but I think it's a dynamic you have to 
be careful of like do we have the right balance of  

850
01:22:19,280 --> 01:22:25,400
people who are super high potential and talented, 
but doing their thing for the first time? Are  

851
01:22:25,400 --> 01:22:30,760
they paired with people who have been there, done 
that, this is not the biggest job of their life,  

852
01:22:30,760 --> 01:22:34,120
and that they can help those people up the 
learning curve faster such that the aggregate  

853
01:22:34,120 --> 01:22:41,040
learning curve or the aggregate learning 
rate of your company is what it needs to be.

854
01:22:41,040 --> 01:22:47,760
Man, I feel like there's a book 
here of lessons for founders,  

855
01:22:47,760 --> 01:22:50,800
things that you never hear about until-

856
01:22:51,720 --> 01:22:54,840
Mind the seniority gap.

857
01:22:54,840 --> 01:22:58,720
That's one of so many. People think about 
becoming founders, they start companies, "Oh, I'm  

858
01:22:58,720 --> 01:23:02,760
going to start a company, there we go." And then, 
they think about that first part of the journey  

859
01:23:02,760 --> 01:23:07,560
that you talked about. And most people don't 
even get that part. And the best case scenario  

860
01:23:07,560 --> 01:23:13,880
is you experience a ton of growth. And then, 
the way you described it to me previously is  

861
01:23:13,880 --> 01:23:19,040
you hit the final bosses where showing all the 
success and they're like, "Oh, I see there's a  

862
01:23:19,040 --> 01:23:24,120
big market here. Let's go after it." And you're 
battling Apple and Google and Microsoft and Meta,  

863
01:23:24,120 --> 01:23:28,480
and a lot of people don't think about that 
and how that's the future if you do well.

864
01:23:28,480 --> 01:23:32,880
Yeah, every time you move up a league, your 
reward is a stronger and better opponent and  

865
01:23:32,880 --> 01:23:39,880
potentially more unlevel playing field. And 
that's just the way it is. You can't control  

866
01:23:39,880 --> 01:23:45,080
that. All you can control is how you respond. And 
so, you want your company's response to embrace  

867
01:23:45,080 --> 01:23:51,360
that challenge and use it as a mechanism 
to get stronger. Easy to say, hard to do.

868
01:23:51,360 --> 01:23:56,040
Yeah. So maybe just to start reflecting 
on some of the lessons from this journey,  

869
01:23:56,040 --> 01:24:03,160
because there's a lot here. One question people 
may be wondering is, should I even be a founder?  

870
01:24:03,160 --> 01:24:08,520
Should I start a company? A lot of people, there's 
a lot of pain that you've been sharing of the  

871
01:24:08,520 --> 01:24:13,320
challenge of starting companies. What do you tell 
people that are asking you like, "Hey, should I  

872
01:24:13,320 --> 01:24:18,000
start a company? Am I right to be a founder?" 
Is there any advice there that you could share?

873
01:24:18,000 --> 01:24:24,560
I don't know what made me want to be a 
founder. I just showed up that way. And so,  

874
01:24:24,560 --> 01:24:29,080
there's probably some chemical imbalance 
of some form that causes people to do it,  

875
01:24:30,520 --> 01:24:36,560
but I had a lot of insecurity about should I 
be a CEO? Because coming from the technical  

876
01:24:36,560 --> 01:24:39,960
side, because I was like, I can do the engineering 
and technology, but all I know about being a CEO  

877
01:24:39,960 --> 01:24:43,760
is I do not know how to do all of those things 
that CEOs do, and I do not look like that,  

878
01:24:43,760 --> 01:24:49,240
I do not talk like that, it's intimidating.
So I think first is it doesn't have to be an  

879
01:24:49,240 --> 01:24:54,320
all or nothing decision. I mean, obviously 
it's all encompassing decision to become,  

880
01:24:55,200 --> 01:25:01,320
to start a company, but you'll have many points 
along the way where you can keep calibrating.  

881
01:25:01,320 --> 01:25:08,160
And I think the biggest thing is, or advice I 
got from one of the founders of a company where  

882
01:25:08,160 --> 01:25:12,920
I worked was I was like, oh, should I be CEO? 
Should I not be CEO? Should I be CTO? He's like,  

883
01:25:12,920 --> 01:25:17,960
"Look, just try it, be CEO, see how it goes."
Initially, I thought I was like, all right,  

884
01:25:17,960 --> 01:25:23,280
well I'm going to get the company to 100 million 
valuation and the trend will just be going faster,  

885
01:25:23,280 --> 01:25:27,080
faster and faster, faster. And instead of just 
getting thrown off of it, I'll just hit stop  

886
01:25:27,080 --> 01:25:35,440
and retire. And I thought that sounded like a 
great plan. But then, moving to the Bay Area, you  

887
01:25:35,440 --> 01:25:42,320
suddenly meet, you throw a rock and hit 10 people 
who've done that. And what do you learn? This was  

888
01:25:42,320 --> 01:25:46,480
just shocking to me because I talked to one of the 
advisors I mentioned earlier. He's like, "Yeah,  

889
01:25:46,480 --> 01:25:53,480
the day I sold my company was the saddest day 
of my life." I'm like, "What?" As a 24-year-old,  

890
01:25:53,480 --> 01:25:58,520
and he's like, "Yeah. Well, I just felt like the 
company had drifted away from what it was supposed  

891
01:25:58,520 --> 01:26:06,080
to be and I just didn't like it." I think they're 
certain in the founder mode trough where you're  

892
01:26:06,080 --> 01:26:09,200
like, wait, things are screwed up and it's on 
my watch, but I'm not really sure what happened  

893
